  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Edmund Quincy planned to call at Maria Weston Chapman&apos;s house on his way to Worcester, but his wife&apos;s ill health kept him at home. He feels he does not play an important part at conventions. He refers to the &quot;Call&quot; to the Chardon Street Convention and the behavior of Oliver Johnson in regard to it. He is troubled chiefly on William Lloyd Garrison&apos;s account.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The &quot;call&quot; is also mentioned in another letter by Edmund Quincy to Maria Weston Chapman, Oct. 8, 1840, Ms.A.9.2 v.14, p.38.</subfield>
